^But beyond that, I find that our two versions read quite differently -- in some ways, radically so. At the same time, I feel that there is no incongruity in my saying that both versions are equally faithful to the text. So do as Tomo Kataoka suggests -- read the voiced version and then the unvoiced version (or vice versa, as per your preference) -- and see if you don't come away with a more complete understanding of the piece than you would have been afforded otherwise.\

